{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17623554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17623554"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:13:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:13:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16871"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16871"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.05,0.2,0,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9561"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68660"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9561"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16871"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54118"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"7603"},{"type":"tags","id":"8412"},{"type":"tags","id":"9882"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22578"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22581"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68660"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism by which nitric oxide causes vasodilation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stimulates guanylate cyclase to produce cyclic guanosine monophosphate","Blocks calcium channels directly in smooth muscle","Activates adenylate cyclase to produce cyclic adenosine monophosphate","Inhibits noradrenaline release from sympathetic nerves","Increases prostaglandin synthesis in endothelial cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENitric oxide causes vasodilation by \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulating guanylate cyclase to produce cyclic guanosine monophosphate\u003C/strong\u003E (cGMP) in vascular smooth muscle cells. This second messenger leads to smooth muscle relaxation through protein kinase G activation and reduction in intracellular calcium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks calcium channels directly in smooth muscle\u003C/strong\u003E - While reduced calcium is an end result, this occurs through cyclic guanosine monophosphate signalling rather than direct channel blockade\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits noradrenaline release from sympathetic nerves\u003C/strong\u003E - Nitric oxide acts directly on smooth muscle cells rather than through neural mechanisms\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivates adenylate cyclase to produce cyclic adenosine monophosphate\u003C/strong\u003E - Nitric oxide works through guanylate cyclase, not adenylate cyclase\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases prostaglandin synthesis in endothelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E - While prostaglandins can cause vasodilation, this is not the mechanism of nitric oxide\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENitric oxide is produced by endothelial cells in response to shear stress and various chemical mediators. Its vasodilatory effects are crucial for maintaining vascular tone and blood pressure regulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nitric oxide causes vasodilation by stimulating guanylate cyclase to produce cyclic guanosine monophosphate in vascular smooth muscle cells.","Nitric oxide is produced by endothelial cells in response to shear stress and various chemical mediators.","The vasodilatory effects of nitric oxide are important for maintaining vascular tone and blood pressure regulation."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54118"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16871"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54118"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T09:09:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T09:39:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9561"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68660"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}}